<br>It's sort of hard.&nbsp; We decided to take the recommended route to the bottom:&nbsp; the South Kaibab trail.&nbsp; It's a little over seven miles, pretty much all in the sun, a bit steeper than the other south rim trail, and there's no water along the way.&nbsp; This doesn't exactly make it a nice trail, but since it's supposed to take twice as long to hike up, it's a much better downward trail than an upward trail.&nbsp; And anyway it's still a very nice trail, and it's breathtaking -- like we're discovering most of the west to be.<br><br><action-text-attachment sgid="BAh7CEkiCGdpZAY6BkVUSSJXZ2lkOi8vYW4tZXZlbnQvQWN0aXZlU3RvcmFnZTo6QmxvYi83ZmE2MGY4YS00NzA3LTQ3NjMtYTdlNS00MmNlYTBhYzI5M2Y_ZXhwaXJlc19pbgY7AFRJIgxwdXJwb3NlBjsAVEkiD2F0dGFjaGFibGUGOwBUSSIPZXhwaXJlc19hdAY7AFQw--7636a90c0247e33ec573d5ebd8791f27b8c283d9" content-type="image/jpeg" url="https://www.carrie-truman.fyi/rails/active_storage/blobs/eyJfcmFpbHMiOnsibWVzc2FnZSI6IkJBaEpJaWszWm1FMk1HWTRZUzAwTnpBM0xUUTNOak10WVRkbE5TMDBNbU5sWVRCaFl6STVNMllHT2daRlZBPT0iLCJleHAiOm51bGwsInB1ciI6ImJsb2JfaWQifX0=--0f14253ef263d202cb5f9f961bdedffcf02b662e/IMG_3235.jpeg" filename="IMG_3235.jpeg" filesize="142368" width="640" height="480" previewable="true" presentation="gallery" caption="here we are at the top, unsuspecting smiles and fresh faces"><figure class="attachment attachment--preview attachment--jpeg">
    <img src="{% imageUrl 'src/images/IMG_3235.jpeg' %}">

  <figcaption class="attachment__caption">
      here we are at the top, unsuspecting smiles and fresh faces
  </figcaption>
</figure></action-text-attachment><br><br>We breakfasted on egg burritos and potatoes and hopped a shuttle to the trailhead -- it's about two miles away, and we were able to leave the Rugged Prius nearer to the return trail so that we would not have to walk further after walking forever already.&nbsp; We never found a place to weigh our packs, but they were sort of heavy, especially with the four-ish liters of water that we packed along.<br><br><action-text-attachment sgid="BAh7CEkiCGdpZAY6BkVUSSJXZ2lkOi8vYW4tZXZlbnQvQWN0aXZlU3RvcmFnZTo6QmxvYi84ZjJhN2Q4Ny1mNzI5LTQ3ZWQtYjUzZC1lNGU5ZWQxYmMzM2I_ZXhwaXJlc19pbgY7AFRJIgxwdXJwb3NlBjsAVEkiD2F0dGFjaGFibGUGOwBUSSIPZXhwaXJlc19hdAY7AFQw--1bb3e4bfc51f1a5a3d8a5a520267343c4f633d8f" content-type="image/jpeg" url="https://www.carrie-truman.fyi/rails/active_storage/blobs/eyJfcmFpbHMiOnsibWVzc2FnZSI6IkJBaEpJaWs0WmpKaE4yUTROeTFtTnpJNUxUUTNaV1F0WWpVelpDMWxOR1U1WldReFltTXpNMklHT2daRlZBPT0iLCJleHAiOm51bGwsInB1ciI6ImJsb2JfaWQifX0=--cf1530a7c68661986a68792c0c32a73063454306/IMG_3250.jpeg" filename="IMG_3250.jpeg" filesize="131630" width="640" height="480" previewable="true" presentation="gallery" caption="down in the canyon maybe 1000 feet"><figure class="attachment attachment--preview attachment--jpeg">
    <img src="{% imageUrl 'src/images/IMG_3250.jpeg' %}">

  <figcaption class="attachment__caption">
      down in the canyon maybe 1000 feet
  </figcaption>
</figure></action-text-attachment><br><br>We took a lot of pictures of the canyons which I will spare you from in the tiny-view of our journal.&nbsp; We'll see about organizing the full-sized pictures from our trip somewhere nice after we get home.&nbsp; There's also an option of taking a mule train down (or up), but the advice is that you'll still be pretty sore from riding mules all day so you may as well walk.<br><br><action-text-attachment sgid="BAh7CEkiCGdpZAY6BkVUSSJXZ2lkOi8vYW4tZXZlbnQvQWN0aXZlU3RvcmFnZTo6QmxvYi9hYWQzYTU2ZC1hNzYxLTQ0NzYtYWE1MS0wODBiZTY4ZTU2ZDI_ZXhwaXJlc19pbgY7AFRJIgxwdXJwb3NlBjsAVEkiD2F0dGFjaGFibGUGOwBUSSIPZXhwaXJlc19hdAY7AFQw--8da6b7527c3418d44c848bdfd7d3b7b863a0d4a3" content-type="image/jpeg" url="https://www.carrie-truman.fyi/rails/active_storage/blobs/eyJfcmFpbHMiOnsibWVzc2FnZSI6IkJBaEpJaWxoWVdRellUVTJaQzFoTnpZeExUUTBOell0WVdFMU1TMHdPREJpWlRZNFpUVTJaRElHT2daRlZBPT0iLCJleHAiOm51bGwsInB1ciI6ImJsb2JfaWQifX0=--953a06092884f01944237aa68e4db034dc726313/IMG_3240.jpeg" filename="IMG_3240.jpeg" filesize="184522" width="640" height="480" previewable="true" presentation="gallery" caption="mules always have the right-of-way"><figure class="attachment attachment--preview attachment--jpeg">
    <img src="{% imageUrl 'src/images/IMG_3240.jpeg' %}">

  <figcaption class="attachment__caption">
      mules always have the right-of-way
  </figcaption>
</figure></action-text-attachment><br><br>There are a few rest stops on the way down the South Kaibab trail, complete with bathrooms.&nbsp; They are surprisingly clean, and meant that we never had to dig a "cat hole" and practice our aim.&nbsp; As a ranger put it later, the Grand Canyon hike is one of the more "front-country, back-country trails."&nbsp; I was very grateful for this, although we still felt reasonably rugged.<br><br><action-text-attachment sgid="BAh7CEkiCGdpZAY6BkVUSSJXZ2lkOi8vYW4tZXZlbnQvQWN0aXZlU3RvcmFnZTo6QmxvYi9mZmMwZmQxZC00YWU4LTRhNWQtYTgzNC05OGZlNzczZDliM2I_ZXhwaXJlc19pbgY7AFRJIgxwdXJwb3NlBjsAVEkiD2F0dGFjaGFibGUGOwBUSSIPZXhwaXJlc19hdAY7AFQw--6381d7af156321ca6b103fda4a924905098e709c" content-type="image/jpeg" url="https://www.carrie-truman.fyi/rails/active_storage/blobs/eyJfcmFpbHMiOnsibWVzc2FnZSI6IkJBaEpJaWxtWm1Nd1ptUXhaQzAwWVdVNExUUmhOV1F0WVRnek5DMDVPR1psTnpjelpEbGlNMklHT2daRlZBPT0iLCJleHAiOm51bGwsInB1ciI6ImJsb2JfaWQifX0=--847b7d5edbfc2d868e3b75307b3037795df368b4/IMG_3254.jpeg" filename="IMG_3254.jpeg" filesize="114770" width="640" height="480" previewable="true" presentation="gallery" caption="mules also need a break sometimes"><figure class="attachment attachment--preview attachment--jpeg">
    <img src="{% imageUrl 'src/images/IMG_3254.jpeg' %}">

  <figcaption class="attachment__caption">
      mules also need a break sometimes
  </figcaption>
</figure></action-text-attachment><br><br>We followed the sage advice to rest often -- about ten minutes out of every hour.&nbsp; We also started each morning at an "agonizingly slow" pace (more advice that Carrie found on the internet) for a half-hour, and stretched before continuing.<br><br><action-text-attachment sgid="BAh7CEkiCGdpZAY6BkVUSSJXZ2lkOi8vYW4tZXZlbnQvQWN0aXZlU3RvcmFnZTo6QmxvYi9lYjdmZmE4MC1kYjQ0LTQ4NDEtYWVkMC0zMzVhNDNjYTRkNzM_ZXhwaXJlc19pbgY7AFRJIgxwdXJwb3NlBjsAVEkiD2F0dGFjaGFibGUGOwBUSSIPZXhwaXJlc19hdAY7AFQw--f3770a5ac5c8a9eda5723bdb7823d0d1633a34bb" content-type="image/jpeg" url="https://www.carrie-truman.fyi/rails/active_storage/blobs/eyJfcmFpbHMiOnsibWVzc2FnZSI6IkJBaEpJaWxsWWpkbVptRTRNQzFrWWpRMExUUTROREV0WVdWa01DMHpNelZoTkROallUUmtOek1HT2daRlZBPT0iLCJleHAiOm51bGwsInB1ciI6ImJsb2JfaWQifX0=--68f91d8c0b9ad2f6b3e3beda7a626d9d2b2d4c11/IMG_3272.jpeg" filename="IMG_3272.jpeg" filesize="145005" width="640" height="480" previewable="true" presentation="gallery" caption="not this kind of stretching, but we did that too"><figure class="attachment attachment--preview attachment--jpeg">
    <img src="{% imageUrl 'src/images/IMG_3272.jpeg' %}">

  <figcaption class="attachment__caption">
      not this kind of stretching, but we did that too
  </figcaption>
</figure></action-text-attachment><br><br>The views were incredible.&nbsp; It's one thing to see the canyon laid out before you at the rim, but it's hard to grasp how big it is until you're down inside of it.&nbsp; Trekking poles help a ton to save your knees on the descent.<br><br><action-text-attachment sgid="BAh7CEkiCGdpZAY6BkVUSSJXZ2lkOi8vYW4tZXZlbnQvQWN0aXZlU3RvcmFnZTo6QmxvYi9jM2RiMmI0YS0xY2FkLTQyMTMtYjVkOC1kZmFkOGYwMGVkMmM_ZXhwaXJlc19pbgY7AFRJIgxwdXJwb3NlBjsAVEkiD2F0dGFjaGFibGUGOwBUSSIPZXhwaXJlc19hdAY7AFQw--bdf02520bbaf881e720a2e434d298913e8eb56e9" content-type="image/jpeg" url="https://www.carrie-truman.fyi/rails/active_storage/blobs/eyJfcmFpbHMiOnsibWVzc2FnZSI6IkJBaEpJaWxqTTJSaU1tSTBZUzB4WTJGa0xUUXlNVE10WWpWa09DMWtabUZrT0dZd01HVmtNbU1HT2daRlZBPT0iLCJleHAiOm51bGwsInB1ciI6ImJsb2JfaWQifX0=--8327a8b5686752f6837e348af32a6604c4cfe3cf/IMG_3289.jpeg" filename="IMG_3289.jpeg" filesize="181294" width="640" height="853" previewable="true" presentation="gallery" caption="they also make you look super cool"><figure class="attachment attachment--preview attachment--jpeg">
